    "summary": "Outreach exposes a REST API and MCP server, both using user OAuth bearer auth; the REST API also supports limited S2S JWT-based bearer auth, while Data Sharing is documented but auth was not determined.",
    "credentials": {
      "outreach_oauth_app": {
        "type": "oauth2",
        "label": "Outreach OAuth app credentials",
        "generateUrl": "https://developers.outreach.io/apps/",
        "setup": "Create an Outreach app in the [Development Portal](https://developers.outreach.io/apps/) and open the app's **API access** tab. Configure at least one redirect URI and one OAuth scope. Outreach provisions **development** credentials immediately for testing; production credentials appear after publishing/review. Copy the `client_id` and the `client_secret` when they are shown, because the secret is only displayed once. To use the API, complete the standard OAuth 2.0 authorization-code flow against `https://api.outreach.io/oauth/authorize` and exchange the code at `https://api.outreach.io/oauth/token`."
      },
      "outreach_s2s_app": {
        "type": "jwt",
        "label": "Outreach S2S app token credentials",
        "generateUrl": "https://developers.outreach.io/api/s2s-access",
        "setup": "In the [API access (S2S)](https://developers.outreach.io/api/s2s-access) section of your Outreach app, enable S2S access, choose the allowed API scopes, and upload one or more PEM-encoded public keys. Outreach then assigns an `S2S_GUID` for the app. Keep the matching RSA private key locally; you sign a short-lived JWT with `iss` set to the `S2S_GUID` to create the app token, then exchange that app token plus the org's `INSTALL_ID` for an S2S access token. The docs also describe obtaining `INSTALL_ID` either from the install setup token flow or from app-installation webhooks."
      }
    },
